{
  "card_id": "market_maker_model",
  "type": "merged_concept",
  "canonical_term": "Market Maker Model",
  "aliases": [],
  "school": "ICT",
  "definition": "A framework using the buy and sell sides of the market maker curve; order blocks formed on one side become mitigation blocks on the other, providing reaccumulation or redistribution zones after a smart money reversal. Alternatively, a price delivery pattern where institutional algorithms execute a sellside delivery taking out lows, then a buyside delivery taking out highs, or vice versa, to engage liquidity before reversing.",
  "identification_rules": [
    "Identify a smart money reversal (market structure shift) on the chart.",
    "On the prior trend side, locate order blocks (up-close or down-close candles) that were previously respected.",
    "Confirm price has closed through these old order blocks, discrediting them.",
    "Drag the disrespected order blocks forward as mitigation blocks.",
    "Look for price retesting these mitigation blocks, often with a PD array like a fair value gap, for entry.",
    "Identify areas of equal highs as buyside liquidity and equal lows as sellside liquidity.",
    "In a bullish scenario, price first breaks below a swing low (sellside delivery) then rallies to break above a swing high (buyside delivery).",
    "In a bearish scenario, price first breaks above a swing high (buyside delivery) then declines to break below a swing low (sellside delivery).",
    "The moves should occur during liquid trading sessions (e.g., London open) to confirm institutional participation."
  ],
  "trading_implication": "Provides high-probability zones for continuation entries after a reversal, using old order blocks from the opposite side of the curve as reaccumulation or redistribution areas. The model reveals engineered liquidity grabs that trap traders on both sides; traders can anticipate a reversal after a liquidity sweep and align entries with the second delivery, but exact timing is difficult. Adds confluence with other PD arrays.",
  "common_mistakes": [
    "Trading mitigation blocks that were not preceded by a liquidity sweep or SMT confirmation, leading to failure swings that become targets.",
    "Confusing mitigation blocks with breaker blocks (mitigation: low, high, higher low, higher high; breaker: low, high, lower low, higher high).",
    "Assuming institutions only target retail stops; they also hunt other institutional participants.",
    "Attempting to trade in both directions (selling the sellside delivery and buying the buyside delivery) without clear reversal confirmation.",
    "Expecting the pattern to always complete perfectly; future movements remain unpredictable."
  ],
  "related_concepts": [],
  "merge_strategy": "llm_synthesis",
  "merge_model": "deepseek/deepseek-chat",
  "merge_notes": "Two different framings: ICT defines MMM as order blocks becoming mitigation blocks; SMC defines it as a liquidity sweep pattern. Both are valid; unified card includes both sets of identification rules. School conflict: ICT vs SMC; picked ICT by majority (1 ICT, 1 SMC, but ICT is the canonical school).",
  "warnings": [
    "school_conflict: ['ICT', 'Smart Money Concepts (SMC)']"
  ],
